ance` could introduce some challenges since it requires the elementType parameter. Maybe it's worth inspecting the metadata file since it might only contain the array type entry. I think including required metadata and generating bean class entries from the public API is the best move, avoiding unnecessary `Class.forName` calls. Let's clarify this further!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating git patching options**\\n\\nI need to inspect where to add entries in my git project. I might consider using `git checkout --patch`, but I think a simpler method would be to create a patch file between HEAD and my desired changes. I could use `git apply --cached` to stage it. However, I have unrelated modifications in my working tree. If the old context matches HEAD, I can still stage only my patch. Then, I could commit my changes separately.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_8MC97l9tWhY9P8MFyDngVhoI|fc_0dd84a19326459070169f0248890f4819ea01c246c9e37e965", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.fasterxml.jackson.jr/jackson-jr-objects/2.21.0/src/test/java/com_fasterxml_jackson_jr/jackson_jr_objects/CollectionBuilderDynamicAccessTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "public class CollectionBuilderDynamicAccessTest {\n    @Test\n    void readsEmptyTypedArrays() throws Exception {\n        String[] values = JSON.std.arrayOfFrom(String.class, \"[]\");\n\n        assertThat(values).isEmpty();\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void readsSingletonTypedArrays() throws Exception {\n        String[] values = JSON.std.arrayOfFrom(String.class, \"[\\\"solo\\\"]\");\n\n        assertThat(values).containsExactly(\"solo\");\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void readsMultiValueTypedArrays() throws Exception {\n        String[] values = JSON.std.arrayOfFrom(String.class, \"[\\\"left\\\",\\\"right\\\"]\");\n\n        assertThat(values).containsExactly(\"left\", \"right\");\n    }\n}\n", "newText": "public class CollectionBuilderDynamicAccessTest {\n    @Test\n    void readsEmptyTy